{"cursor":"32468","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox philosopher \n| region = Western Philosophy era = Renaissance philosophy\n\n| image = Michel de Montaigne 1.jpg caption = birth_name = Michel Eyquem de\n| Montaigne birth_date = 28 February 1533 birth_place = ChÃ¢teau de Montaigne\n| death_date = death_place = ChÃ¢teau de Montaigne school_tradition = Renaissance\n| humanism Renaissance skepticism influences = Horace, Heraclitus, Sextus\n| Empiricus, Seneca, Plutarch, Cato influenced = William Shakespeare, RenÃ©\n| Descartes, Friedrich Nietzsche, Jean-FranÃ§ois Lyotard, Ralph Waldo Emerson,\n| Blaise Pascal, Gore Vidal, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, William Hazlitt, Eric\n| Hoffer, Michel Onfray, JosÃ© Saramago [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/bfaf51ba-e05a-11de-8494-\n| 00144feab49a.html#axzz1L3wH1OFW FT.com \"Small Talk: JosÃ© Saramago\"].\n| \"Everything Iâve read has influenced me in some way. Having said that, Kafka,\n| Borges, Gogol, Montaigne, Cervantes are constant companions.\"\n| notable_ideas = The essay, Montaigne's wheel\n| argument religion = Roman Catholic\n}}\n\n'Michel Eyquem de Montaigne' (; 28 February 1533 â 13 September 1592) was\none of the most influential writers of the French Renaissance, known for\npopularising the essay as a literary genre, and commonly thought of as the\nfather of modern skepticism. He became famous for his effortless ability to\nmerge serious intellectual exercises with casual anecdotes His anecdotes are\n'casual' only in appearance; Montaigne writes: 'Neither my anecdotes nor my\nquotations are always employed simply as examples, for authority, or for\nornament . .They often carry, off the subject under discussion, the seed of a\nricher and more daring matter, and they resonate obliquely with a more delicate\ntone,' Michel de Montagne, Essais PlÃ©iade, Paris (ed.A.Thibaudet) 1937,\nBk.1,ch.40 p.252 (tr.Charles Rosen) and autobiographyâand his massive\nvolume [[Essais]] (translated literally as \"Attempts\" or \"Trials\") contains, to\nthis day, some of the most widely influential essays ever written. Montaigne had\na direct influence on writers the world over, including RenÃ©\nDescartes, Buckley, Michael J., At the Origins of Modern Atheism, Yale UP,\n1990, p. 69. Blaise Pascal, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, William Hazlitt, Kinnaird, John, William Hazlitt: Critic of Power,\nColumbia University Press, 1978, p. 274. Ralph Waldo Emerson, Friedrich\nNietzsche, Stefan Zweig, Eric Hoffer, from Truth Imagined, memoir by Eric\nHoffer. Isaac Asimov, and possibly on the later works of William\nShakespeare.\n\nIn his own time, Montaigne was admired more as a statesman than as an author.\nThe tendency in his essays to digress into anecdotes and personal ruminations\nwas seen as detrimental to proper style rather than as an innovation, and his\ndeclaration that, 'I am myself the matter of my book', was viewed by his\ncontemporaries as self-indulgent. In time, however, Montaigne would be\nrecognized as embodying, perhaps better than any other author of his time, the\nspirit of freely entertaining doubt which began to emerge at that time. He is\nmost famously known for his skeptical remark, 'Que sÃ§ay-je?' ('What do I know?'\nin Middle French; modern French Que sais-je?). Remarkably modern even to\nreaders today, Montaigne's attempt to examine the world through the lens of the\nonly thing he can depend on implicitlyâhis own judgmentâmakes him more\naccessible to modern readers than any other author of the Renaissance. Much of\nmodern literary non-fiction has found inspiration in Montaigne and writers of\nall kinds continue to read him for his masterful balance of intellectual\nknowledge and personal story-telling.\n","linknr":508,"url":"Michel_de_Montaigne","recorded":1375088202,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Michel_de_Montaigne&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Michel_de_Montaigne&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia